The '''dimensions and shape of the [[vagina|human vagina]]''' are of great importance in [[medicine]] and [[surgery]];<ref name=upenn2006/> there appears to be no one way, however, to characterize the vagina's size and shape.<ref name=upenn2006/> In addition to variations in size and shape from individual to individual, a single woman's vagina can vary substantially in size and shape during [[sexual arousal]] and [[sexual intercourse]].<ref name=Lawrence2011/> [[Parity (biology)|Parity]] is associated with a significant increase in the length of the [[vaginal fornix]].<ref name=upenn2006/> The potential effect of parity may be via stretching and elongation of the [[birth canal]] at the time of [[Childbirth#Vaginal birth|vaginal birth]].<ref name=upenn2006/>
Although the dimensions of the human vagina have not been the subject of intensive research to the same extent as research into [[human penis size]],<ref name=upenn2006/> a number of research studies have been made of the dimensions of the human vagina.
== Dimensions in the baseline state == A 1996 study by Pendergrass et al., using [[vinyl polysiloxane]] castings taken from the vaginas of 39 [[White American|Caucasian]] women, found the following ranges of dimensions:<ref name=Pendergrass1996>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1159/000291946 | last1 = Pendergrass | first1 = P. B. | last2 = Reeves | first2 = C. A. | last3 = Belovicz | first3 = M. W. | last4 = Molter | first4 = D. J. | last5 = White | first5 = J. H. | title = The shape and dimensions of the human vagina as seen in three-dimensional vinyl polysiloxane casts | journal = Gynecologic and Obstetric Investigation | volume = 42 | issue = 3 | pages = 178–182 | year = 1996 | pmid = 8938470 }}</ref> * lengths (measured using rods): {{convert|6.9|to|15|cm|abbr=on}}; * widths: {{convert|4.8|to|6.3|cm|abbr=on}}; * introital diameters: {{convert|2.4|to|6.5|cm|abbr=on}}
A second study by the same group showed significant variations in size and shape between the vaginas of women of different ethnic groups.<ref name="Pendergrass2000">{{Cite journal | last1 = Pendergrass | first1 = P. B. | last2 = Reeves | first2 = C. A. | last3 = Belovicz | first3 = M. W. | last4 = Molter | first4 = D. J. | last5 = White | first5 = J. H. | title = Comparison of vaginal shapes in Afro-American, Caucasian and Hispanic women as seen with vinyl polysiloxane casting | doi = 10.1159/000010281 | journal = Gynecologic and Obstetric Investigation | volume = 50 | issue = 1 | pages = 54–59 | year = 2000 | pmid = 10895030| pmc = }}</ref> Both studies showed a wide range of vaginal shapes, described by the researchers as "Parallel sided, conical, heart, [...] slug"<ref name="Pendergrass1996"/> and "pumpkin seed"<ref name=Pendergrass2000/> shapes. Barnhart et al., however, weren't find any correlation amongst the race and the size of vagina. They were also unable to characterize the vaginal shape as a "heart, slug, pumpkin seed or parallel sides" as suggested by the previous studies.<ref name="upenn2006"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesocial.ca/wellness/health/how-much-do-you-know-about-vaginas?app=CTVGO|title=The Social - How much do you know about vaginas?|website=TheSocial.ca|access-date=1 January 2018}}</ref> A 2003 study by the group of Pendergrass et al. also using castings as a measurement method, measured vaginal surface areas ranging from {{convert|66|to|107|cm2|abbr=on}} with a mean of {{convert|87|cm2|abbr=on}} and a standard deviation of {{convert|7.8|cm2|abbr=on}}<ref>.{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1159/000070184 | last1 = Pendergrass | first1 = P. B. | last2 = Belovicz | first2 = M. W. | last3 = Reeves | first3 = C. A. | title = Surface area of the human vagina as measured from vinyl polysiloxane casts | journal = Gynecologic and Obstetric Investigation | volume = 55 | issue = 2 | pages = 110–113 | year = 2003 | pmid = 12771458 }}</ref>
Research published in 2006 by Barnhart et al., gave the following mean dimensions, based on [[MRI scan]]s of 28 women:<ref name="upenn2006">{{Cite journal | last1 = Barnhart | first1 = K. T. | last2 = Izquierdo | first2 = A. | last3 = Pretorius | first3 = E. S. | last4 = Shera | first4 = D. M. | last5 = Shabbout | first5 = M. | last6 = Shaunik | first6 = A. | title = Baseline dimensions of the human vagina | doi = 10.1093/humrep/del022 | journal = Human Reproduction | volume = 21 | issue = 6 | pages = 1618–1622 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16478763 | pmc = }}</ref>
* Mean length from [[cervix]] to [[introitus]]: {{convert|6.3|cm|abbr=on}}. * Mean width: ** at the proximal vagina: {{convert|3.3|cm|abbr=on}}; ** at the [[pelvic diaphragm]]: {{convert|2.7|cm|abbr=on}}; ** at the introitus: {{convert|2.6|cm|abbr=on}}
== Dimensions during sexual arousal == Lawrence, citing [[Masters and Johnson]]'s ''[[Human sexual response cycle|Human Sexual Response]]'' (1966), states that pages 73 and 74 of that book show that typical vaginal depth in Masters and Johnson's participants ranged from 7–8&nbsp;cm (2.8–3.1&nbsp;in) in an unstimulated state, to 11–12&nbsp;cm (4.3–4.7&nbsp;in) during [[sexual arousal]] with a [[Speculum (medical)|speculum]] in place.<ref name=Lawrence2011/>
== Dimensions of medical devices used in the vagina == There does not appear to be large variation in the dimensions of the vagina within the same woman.<ref name=upenn2006/> Given the large range in the dimensions noted, it is most likely that one size for a [[pessary|vaginal device]] will not fit all vaginas.<ref name=upenn2006/>
== Dimensions in pregnancy and childbirth == {{empty section|date=July 2013}}
== Dimensions of surgically created neovaginas == The depth of the typical [[neovagina]] created by [[male-to-female sex reassignment surgery]] is generally limited by the length of [[Denonvilliers' fascia]],{{citation needed|date=May 2013}} and is reported to be between 11 and 12&nbsp;cm (4.3-4.7&nbsp;in), within the range of the natural female vagina.<ref name=Lawrence2011>{{cite web|url=http://www.annelawrence.com/genitaldimensions.html|title=Notes on Genital Dimensions|author=Anne A. Lawrence|accessdate=2012-05-13}}</ref>
