{{Infobox hospital | Name = '''Queen Ingrid's Hospital''' | Org/Group = | Image = | image alt = | Caption = | map_type = Greenland | coordinates = {{coord|64.16916|-51.73805|display=inline,title}} | map_caption = | Logo = | Logo Size = | Location = [[Nuuk]] | Region = | State = | Country = [[Greenland]] | HealthCare = | Funding = Government | Type = General | Speciality = | Standards = | Emergency = | Helipad = | Affiliation = | Patron = | Network = | Beds = 130 | Founded = 1953 | Closed = | Website = | Wiki-Links = [http://peqqik.gl/Footerpages/English.aspx?sc_lang=kl-GL www.peqqik.gl] }}
'''Queen Ingrid's Hospital''' ({{lang-kl|Dronning Ingridip Napparsimmavissua}}) is a hospital in [[Nuuk]], [[Greenland]]. The hospital not only serves as the main hospital for the municipality but is the central hospital in all of Greenland. The hospital has 185 beds.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Niclasen |first1=Birgit |last2=Mulvad |first2=Gurt |title=Health care and health care delivery in Greenland |journal=International Journal of Circumpolar Health |date=2010 |volume=69 |issue=5 |pages=437-487 |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.3402/ijch.v69i5.17691 |accessdate=18 November 2018}}</ref> There is a 12 bed psychiatric ward. Some forensic patients have to be transferred to a special ward in Denmark.<ref>{{cite web |title=Agency for Health and Prevention (Greenland) |url=http://mastermind-project.eu/partners/agency-for-health-and-prevention-greenland/ |website=Mastermind Project |accessdate=18 November 2018}}</ref>
==History== The hospital was established in 1953 and initially was a sanatorium for [[Pulmonology|pulmonary diseases]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Archives of environmental health, Volume 17|publisher=[[American Medical Association]], American Academy of Occupational Medicine, Society for Occupational and Environmental Healthm Heldref Publications|year=1968}}</ref>
==Architecture== The current hospital complex dates from 1980 but is currently being expanded and rejuvenated according to a plan by [[C. F. Møller Architects]].<ref name=Architecture>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/index.php?fuseaction=wanappln.projectview&upload_id=16039 |title=Go with the floe... |publisher=World Architecture News |accessdate=2011-02-07}}</ref>
The first phase which consists of a health centre and pharmacy opened on 3 February 2011. It take the form of sunken angular blocks and is clad in copper both on the facades and roof. The design is inspired by the ice floes that float in [[Godthåbsfjord]] and the image of [[Sermitsiaq (mountain)|Sermitsiaq]], a 1210 meters high mountain and local landmark, symbol for Nuuk municipality before municipal mergers in 2009, however Sermitsiaq is not Greenland’s highest mountain, (Gunnbjørn Fjeldet, 3694 meter high in Eastgreenland is the highest in Greenland).<ref name=Architecture/>
Also planned are a psychiatric building, rural pharmacy and a new medical clinic for general practitioners as well a circular patient ‘hotel’ with additional beds.<ref name=Architecture/>
