'''Thomas Clarion''' (born 15 March 1982) is a French male visually impaired [[Paralympic cross-country skiing|cross-country skier]] and [[Paralympic biathlon|biathlete]] who is also well known as a [[physiotherapist]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/news/three-reasons-why-thomas-clarion-loves-skiing|title=Thomas Clarion's reasons to be successful in Paralympic Nordic skiing|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref> He has competed at the [[Winter Paralympics]] in [[2010 Winter Paralympics|2010]], [[2014 Winter Paralympics|2014]] and [[2018 Winter Paralympics|2018]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pyeongchang2018.com/en/game-time/results/PWG2018/en/cross-country-skiing/athlete-profile-n3092198-thomas-clarion.htm|title=Cross-Country Skiing {{!}} Athlete Profile: Thomas CLARION - Pyeongchang 2018 Paralympic Winter Games|website=www.pyeongchang2018.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref>

== Career ==
Thomas Clarion competed in his first Paralympic event in [[2010 Winter Paralympics|2010]] and went medalless during the competition. He claimed 2 bronze medals at the [[2014 Winter Paralympics]] in the [[Cross-country skiing at the 2014 Winter Paralympics – Men's 10 km|men's 10km cross-country skiing event]] and [[Cross-country skiing at the 2014 Winter Paralympics – 4 x 2.5 kilometre open relay|4 x 2.5 km relay open event]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.paralympic.org/asp/lib/TheASP.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=-1&personid=919327&WinterGames=-1|title=Thomas Clarion|last=|first=|date=|website=Paralympic.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref>

He went onto represent [[France at the 2018 Winter Paralympics]], his third Paralympic event and managed to claim a bronze medal in the [[Cross-country skiing at the 2018 Winter Paralympics – Men's 20 kilometre free|men's 20km free visually impaired cross-country skiing event]] which was also his third Paralympic medal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.paralympic.org/thomas-clarion|title=Thomas Clarion {{!}} Paralympic bio|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pyeongchang2018.com/en/game-time/results/PWG2018/en/cross-country-skiing/results-men-s-20km-free-visually-impaired-fnl-000100-.htm|title=Cross-Country Skiing {{!}} Results Men's 20km Free, Visually Impaired - Pyeongchang 2018 Paralympic Winter Games|website=www.pyeongchang2018.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mobile.lemonde.fr/jeux-olympiques-pyeongchang-2018/article/2018/03/12/jeux-paralympiques-2018-benjamin-daviet-remporte-l-argent_5269323_5193626.html?xtref=https://fr.m.wikipedia.org/|title=Jeux paralympiques 2018 : trois médailles françaises décrochées lundi|website=Le Monde.fr|language=fr-FR|access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref> He claimed his first Paralympic gold medal during the [[2018 Winter Paralympics]] after winning the men's 4 x 2.5&nbsp;km relay open team event for [[France at the 2018 Winter Paralympics|France]] along with other members including [[Benjamin Daviet]] and [[Anthony Chalençon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pyeongchang2018.com/en/game-time/results/PWG2018/en/cross-country-skiing/results-4x2-5km-open-relay-fnl-000100-.htm|title=Cross-Country Skiing {{!}} Results 4x2.5km Open Relay - Pyeongchang 2018 Paralympic Winter Games|website=www.pyeongchang2018.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>

